    {
        "user": "UJBAJNFLK",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1729578357.840239",
        "client_msg_id": "b639ec54-c1a8-4e83-8e95-fc367249a053",
        "text": "I very much agree that it takes both reading and running to engage with code, and that's indeed a major issue with traditional LP. Also with Open Source, btw, which suggests that having full access to the code is enough to understand and modify code, even if it's a huger mess and impossible to build.\n\nThat said, integrating code with a narrative becomes very relevant when you also add data (via visualizations). It's not code you engage with then, but data, computational models, etc. This is the reason why notebooks were so much more successful than traditional code-centric LP.\n\nOne major weakness of notebooks is the single narrative. What I would like to have is a graph of narratives, code, and data, everything being interactive. I am aware of two real-life systems that enable this: <https:\/\/gtoolkit.com\/|Glamorous Toolkit> and <https:\/\/webstrates.net\/|Webstrates>.",
